63m.title: Universal property of the disjoint union
63m.clickbait: Just as the empty set may be described by a universal property, so too may the disjoint union of sets.
63m.text:
[summary: The [-5z9] may be described by a [-600] which is very similar to that of the [5zv universal property of the product]. Specifically, the disjoint union of sets $A$ and $B$ is a set denoted $A \sqcup B$ together with maps $\i_A : A \to A \sqcup B$ and $\i_B: B \to A \sqcup B$, such that for every set $X$ and every pair of maps $f_A: A \to X$ and $f_B: B \to X$, there is a unique map $\gamma: A \sqcup B \to X$ such that $\gamma \circ i_A = f_A$ and $\gamma \circ i_B = f_B$.]

[summary(Technical): The [-5z9] may be described as the [-coproduct] in the [4c7 category] of [3jz sets]. Specifically, the disjoint union of sets $A$ and $B$ is a set denoted $A \sqcup B$ together with maps $\i_A : A \to A \sqcup B$ and $\i_B: B \to A \sqcup B$, such that for every set $X$ and every pair of maps $f_A: A \to X$ and $f_B: B \to X$, there is a unique map $\gamma: A \sqcup B \to X$ such that $\gamma \circ i_A = f_A$ and $\gamma \circ i_B = f_B$.]

Where could we start if we were looking for a [-600] describing the [5s8 union of sets]?

The first thing to notice is that universal properties only identify objects up to isomorphism, but the union is *not* really [-5ss] up to isomorphism.

%%hidden(The union is not well-defined up to isomorphism):
Consider $A = \{ 1 \}$ and $B = \{ 1 \}$.
Then the union $A \cup B$ is equal to $\{1\}$.

On the other hand, consider $X = \{1\}$ and $Y = \{2\}$.
Then the union $X \cup Y = \{1,2\}$.

So by replacing $A$ with the isomorphic $X$, and $B$ with the isomorphic $Y$, we have obtained $\{1,2\}$ which is *not* isomorphic to $\{1\} = A \cup B$.
%%

Therefore we can't reasonably hope to capture the union with a universal property.
But the next best thing is the *[5z9 disjoint union]* $A \sqcup B$, which is well-defined up to isomorphism: the definition of $A \sqcup B$ is constructed so that even if $A$ and $B$ overlap, the intersection still doesn't get treated any differently.

[todo: observe that it's the same as the reversed product]
